<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05149c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05149c">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05149c"> 149(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Old Marcus Appius <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n05149c"> <li>FW unlocated</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Ad Appi Claudi senectutem accedebat etiam, ut caecus esset; tamen is, cum sententia senatus inclinaret ad placem cum Pyrrho foedusque faciendum, non dubitavit dicere illa, quae versibus persecutus est Ennius: <br>&ldquo;Quo vobis mentes, rectae quae stare solebant <br> Antehac, dementis sese flexere viai?&rdquo; <br>ceteraque gravissime; notum enim vobis carmen est; et tamen ipsius Appi exstat oratio. <br>To old age Appius Claudius had the additional disadvantage of being blind; yet it was he who, when the Senate was inclining towards a peace with Pyrrhus and was for making a treaty, did not hesitate to say what Ennius has embalmed in the verses: <br>&ldquo;Whither have swerved the souls so firm of yore? <br>Is sense grown senseless? Can feet stand no more?&rdquo; <br>And so on in a tone of the most passionate vehemence. <small> Marcus Tullius Cicero, <a name="CATO" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CATO"><cite title="source">De Senectute</cite></a> (Edition of 1902) 16</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n05098g" href="n05all.htm#n05098g">N05 (VI.B.2):098(g)</a> </mm> </dd></dl>
